<BR>

It is not I that change, only how you perceive me.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uaramalg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aramalg</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 140<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/30/01 11:48:33 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> re:The Wizard Epic.</span><hr size=1>   I am not really talking about how effective the epic is, symphony.  Instead I am going more for the “appropriate” angle.<br>
  Yes, the boosted manaskin is nice.  Especially since it doesn’t cost a peridot to cast.  Yet how appropriate is this for the wizard class?  Defensive skins are not something that I would call inherently wizards.  Necromancers, enchanters and druids all get a form of the same type of spell.  With some variation, of course.  So a boosted skin spell could easily have been given to any of those three classes.  It could even be argued that the druids got a castable version of our epic which was better in some regards.  That is debatable of course and isn’t really the point.<br>
  The point as I see it, is that while the skin effect on the wizard epic is good, it isn’t really in line with the class.  This is of course open to interpretation, but to me that epic effect isn’t what I would have chosen for the class.  An extra offensive spell would have been nice.  Yes, you can argue the aggro point, but to me that isn’t a valid argument.  Not really.  Wizards have been dealing with aggro for a long time.  I really can’t see us killing ourselves repeatedly if our epic had a good damage spell as a right click effect.  Lol, not after the first few times anyway.  I can understand why an offensive spell wouldn’t be wanted though.  Yet there are still other options.<br>
  Some alternative wizard epic effects.<br>
  A 25% increase to mana regeneration.  Maybe more.  It gives you the potential to do more damage, but not in a soloing situation.  Not really.  This would, in my opinion, be good for groups, where wizards can find themselves easily running low on mana if the pull rate is high.<br>
  Another idea is to have a one in four chance of doing a double spellcast.  What I mean by this is that every time you cast a spell, a check would be made.  If you miss your check, the spell goes on to land as normal.  If you make it the spell will land twice.  You only receive the aggro for the initial spell though.<br>
  You could have the effect of the staff be that all spells cast by the wizard when they are holding the staff it is as if an unresistible spell has been cast.  This would allow you to use your mana efficient spells instead of lures.<br>
  There are lots of possible effects they could have chosen, some better and more practical than others.  While the skin is good, I really don’t think it is appropriate as the effect of our epic weapon.<br>
<br>
Talinath.<br>
