<img src="http://pages.cthome.net/filanwizard/mtasig.gif"></a></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/uaramalg.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Aramalg</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 144<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(8/31/01 11:38:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=18.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> re:The Wizard Epic.</span><hr size=1>   I am not talking about the stats or how good or useful the epic is.  What I am talking about is whether or not the skin effect that we have been given is something that truly represents what the wizard class stands for.<br>
  Yes, a damage spell would be nice.  However, the same argument about the skin could be used on such a spell unless the spell in question was some sort of lure or better version of disintegrate.  So the only way a damage spell on the epic would be justified would be if it was something uniquely related to the wizard class.  I realise that the effects on other epics are not “unique” to the class, but those effects are, in my opinion, strongly associated with the class.<br>
  Let me put it this way.  If I asked you to tell me the two things that most strongly represent the wizard class in your mind, what would you say?  My guess is that it would be something to do with our damage output/potential and our teleports.  I really doubt that you would say our magical skins.  Magical skins are useful, but they are not, in my opinion, a key element of the wizard class.  If I was to take away our ability to cast magical skins, would it drastically change the wizard class?  I don’t think so.  It might make some encounters more difficult and we would die more often, but that is about it.<br>
  Taking all of what I have just mentioned in mind, let me ask again, why do we have a skin effect on our epic?  Nice though the effect is, it is not appropriate to the wizard class.  Not as an epic effect anyway.  Out of the alternative effects I mentioned in the post above, the one that I personally like the most is that of being able to land any spell unresisted on mobs.  The lures show that the wizard class has been working towards this, so it would be an understandable progression.  I think so anyway.<br>
<br>
